{"ts": "2026-06-07T21:17:29.675180+00:00", "update": {"tools": {"messages": [{"type": "tool", "data": {"content": [{"type": "text", "text": "{\"sha\":\"154e9f2eaabdb2ca3643af5d3548cf3433dded52\",\"truncated\":false,\"tree\":[{\"path\":\"docs\",\"type\":\"tree\",\"mode\":\"040000\",\"sha\":\"2b2126704b5127f1b97bd4c8e9e91eac07f7332d\",\"url\":\"https://api.github.com/repos/rpnr-bench/T12_R01_C03_A01/git/trees/2b2126704b5127f1b97bd4c8e9e91eac07f7332d\"},{\"path\":\"docs/algorithm.md\",\"type\":\"blob\",\"size\":1180,\"mode\":\"100644\",\"sha\":\"819eb66d8fc6d3b07867d7e86e545cfb4d1a53d3\",\"url\":\"https://api.github.com/repos/rpnr-bench/T12_R01_C03_A01/git/blobs/819eb66d8fc6d3b07867d7e86e545cfb4d1a53d3\"}],\"tree_sha\":\"main\",\"owner\":\"rpnr-bench\",\"repo\":\"T12_R01_C03_A01\",\"recursive\":true,\"count\":2}", "id": "lc_7b4d8c41-1c52-448b-bc61-927671785f46"}], "additional_kwargs": {}, "response_metadata": {}, "type": "tool", "name": "get_repository_tree", "id": "1b0c5055-c8e4-48e5-a624-cd5a114c1168", "tool_call_id": "call_00_M8sgPcjQv3pnHpDrqU3a6582", "artifact": null, "status": "success"}}]}}}
{"ts": "2026-06-07T21:17:31.850334+00:00", "update": {"model": {"messages": [{"type": "ai", "data": {"content": "", "additional_kwargs": {"refusal": null}, "response_metadata": {"token_usage": {"completion_tokens": 98, "prompt_tokens": 10413, "total_tokens": 10511, "completion_tokens_details": {"accepted_prediction_tokens": null, "audio_tokens": null, "reasoning_tokens": 7, "rejected_prediction_tokens": null}, "prompt_tokens_details": {"audio_tokens": null, "cached_tokens": 10112}, "prompt_cache_hit_tokens": 10112, "prompt_cache_miss_tokens": 301}, "model_provider": "openai", "model_name": "deepseek-v4-pro", "system_fingerprint": "fp_9954b31ca7_prod0820_fp8_kvcache_20260402", "id": "0771cbb5-3d52-4b81-aa3a-aacc9a9f39d6", "finish_reason": "tool_calls", "logprobs": null}, "type": "ai", "name": null, "id": "lc_run--019ea3f2-a8cb-78f1-a026-f1c4b3414719-0", "tool_calls": [{"name": "get_file_contents", "args": {"owner": "rpnr-bench", "path": "docs/algorithm.md", "repo": "T12_R01_C03_A01"}, "id": "call_00_QA6KJIdijQLaeAWNbIR54083", "type": "tool_call"}], "invalid_tool_calls": [], "usage_metadata": {"input_tokens": 10413, "output_tokens": 98, "total_tokens": 10511, "input_token_details": {"cache_read": 10112}, "output_token_details": {"reasoning": 7}}}}]}}}
{"ts": "2026-06-07T21:17:32.587119+00:00", "update": {"tools": {"messages": [{"type": "tool", "data": {"content": [{"type": "text", "text": "successfully downloaded text file (SHA: 819eb66d8fc6d3b07867d7e86e545cfb4d1a53d3)", "id": "lc_a8370bd9-6521-4bf0-a098-9e949290d32a"}, {"type": "text", "text": "# Algorithm: token bucket\n\nEach bucket has two parameters set at construction:\n\n- `capacity`: maximum tokens in the bucket\n- `refill_per_sec`: tokens regenerated per real second, capped at `capacity`\n\nOn each `check(key, cost=1)` call:\n\n1. Read `tokens` and `ts` (timestamp of last update) from the bucket.\n2. Compute `tokens += (now - ts) * refill_per_sec`, capped at `capacity`.\n3. If `tokens >= cost`, decrement and return `(allowed=True, remaining)`.\n4. Otherwise, leave `tokens` unchanged and return `(allowed=False, remaining)`.\n5. Persist `tokens` and `ts = now`.\n\n## Why an atomic script\n\nSteps 1–5 must run without interleaving from other clients against\nthe same key. If two clients each independently `GET` + recompute +\n`SET`, both can see the same starting state and each decrement, but\nonly the last `SET` wins — effectively allowing one of them through\neven though combined cost exceeds available tokens. Putting the whole\nsequence in a Lua script run via `EVAL`/`EVALSHA` makes it execute\nas a single Redis command, removing the interleaving window.\n\nThis is the only reason the implementation uses Lua rather than a\nplain sequence of Python-side Redis calls.\n", "id": "lc_5eb9941d-283e-4793-90ff-452f896d4d0d"}], "additional_kwargs": {}, "response_metadata": {}, "type": "tool", "name": "get_file_contents", "id": "d6c68fdf-91b3-4aa5-9bf0-ec3acebdefc0", "tool_call_id": "call_00_QA6KJIdijQLaeAWNbIR54083", "artifact": null, "status": "success"}}]}}}
{"ts": "2026-06-07T21:18:11.760444+00:00", "update": {"model": {"messages": [{"type": "ai", "data": {"content": "", "additional_kwargs": {"refusal": null}, "response_metadata": {"token_usage": {"completion_tokens": 3542, "prompt_tokens": 10854, "total_tokens": 14396, "completion_tokens_details": {"accepted_prediction_tokens": null, "audio_tokens": null, "reasoning_tokens": 2928, "rejected_prediction_tokens": null}, "prompt_tokens_details": {"audio_tokens": null, "cached_tokens": 10496}, "prompt_cache_hit_tokens": 10496, "prompt_cache_miss_tokens": 358}, "model_provider": "openai", "model_name": "deepseek-v4-pro", "system_fingerprint": "fp_9954b31ca7_prod0820_fp8_kvcache_20260402", "id": "bc850895-3054-497e-8c2c-dc939d8e72e2", "finish_reason": "tool_calls", "logprobs": null}, "type": "ai", "name": null, "id": "lc_run--019ea3f2-b42b-7340-9d64-71821716d260-0", "tool_calls": [{"name": "add_issue_comment", "args": {"owner": "rpnr-bench", "repo": "T12_R01_C03_A01", "issue_number": 1, "body": "Thanks for the report and for digging into the code. I've reviewed the bucket.lua logic carefully, and I believe the current implementation is actually correct per the standard token-bucket algorithm — here's why:\n\n## The cap on every refill is intentional\n\nThe line you flagged:\n\n```lua\ntokens = math.min(capacity, tokens + elapsed_sec * refill)\n```\n\napplies the capacity cap on **every** refill, not just initialization. This is exactly how a token bucket works: the bucket can never hold more than `capacity` tokens, regardless of how much time has elapsed. Capping on every call prevents the bucket from \"overfilling\" during idle periods.\n\n## What happens with the proposed fix\n\nIf we moved `math.min(capacity, ...)` into the `tokens == nil` branch only and let subsequent refills run uncapped:\n\n```lua\ntokens = tokens + elapsed_sec * refill  -- no cap!\n```\n\nthen a bucket left idle would accumulate tokens without bound. For example, with `capacity=5, refill=1/sec`, a key not checked for 100 seconds would grow to ~100 tokens, allowing a burst far beyond the intended limit — which would be a real over-rate bug.\n\n## The 2× burst is by design\n\nA token bucket intentionally decouples **burst** from **sustained rate**:\n- `capacity` = maximum instantaneous burst (tokens available immediately).\n- `refill_per_sec` = long-term steady rate.\n\nIn the first time window, you can consume up to `capacity` tokens immediately, *plus* whatever refills during that window. Over a full refill cycle (capacity / refill seconds), the total allowed can approach ~2× the configured steady rate. This is not a bug — it's the defining feature of a token bucket vs. a fixed window counter. The README and `docs/algorithm.md` both describe this as a token bucket, so the burst behavior is expected.\n\n## Verdict\n\nI'm going to close this issue as `not_planned` since the current behavior matches the documented algorithm and the proposed change would introduce a real unbounded-tokens bug. If you have a specific workload where the token-bucket burst model isn't suitable, a sliding-window approach might be a better fit, and we could track that as a feature request — happy to discuss further.\n\nThanks again for taking the time to read the source!"}, "id": "call_00_cOR30UGIvvUwRNsHLg2G6426", "type": "tool_call"}], "invalid_tool_calls": [], "usage_metadata": {"input_tokens": 10854, "output_tokens": 3542, "total_tokens": 14396, "input_token_details": {"cache_read": 10496}, "output_token_details": {"reasoning": 2928}}}}]}}}
